    </tags>
    <tools>
      <tool>claude-code</tool>
    </tools>
  </metadata>

  <content>
    <title>MVP Scoping</title>

    <summary>A six-step process for compressing a feature backlog into a minimum viable product: define the core problem, identify the single job the product must do, categorise all features with MoSCoW, validate scope fits the timeline, and define explicit "won't have" and kill-signal criteria. The hard rules: Must-Haves capped at 5, total Must+Should effort must fit the timebox (4-8 weeks), and every scope document requires a learning goal and a failure criterion.</summary>

    <why>
      <p>Founders build either too much (a 6-month "MVP" with 50 features) or too little to deliver value. Without a framework, scope is determined by enthusiasm not evidence. The MoSCoW + timebox combination forces trade-offs to be explicit; the kill-signal requirement prevents the MVP from becoming an unfalsifiable experiment — if you cannot say what evidence kills the idea, you will ship regardless of what you learn.</p>
    </why>

    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Solo founder or small team turning a validated problem into a buildable first slice.</item>
        <item>Existing feature backlog has 30+ ideas and needs compression to a 4-8 week slice.</item>
        <item>Pivot: prior MVP failed, leaner re-scope with explicit "won't have" boundaries needed.</item>
        <item>New vertical or persona entry requiring an anchored smaller release.</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>

    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Problem itself is unvalidated — run product-discovery and problem-validation first.</item>
        <item>Compliance/regulated products (medical, fintech KYC) where "minimum" violates statutory requirements.</item>
        <item>Feature parity migration of a production system — scope is dictated by parity, not learning.</item>
        <item>Mature product with a polished user base; "minimum" disappoints loyal users — use mlp-planning.</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>

    <section name="mvp-definition-and-framework">
      <p>Minimum Viable Product is the smallest version that solves the core problem, delivers value to early adopters, and allows you to learn and iterate. Key insight: MVP is about learning, not launching a polished product.</p>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Start with MVP to validate the core hypothesis, then evolve to MLP for retention. Do not skip validation to go straight to polish.</statement>
        <rationale>Polishing a product before validating demand is expensive. MVP first confirms the problem-solution fit exists; MLP then makes the solution worth keeping.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="moscow-prioritization">
      <p>Categorise every feature as Must Have, Should Have, Could Have, or Won't Have. Must-Have count must not exceed 5. Total effort for Must+Should must fit within the target timebox.</p>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Categorise every feature as Must Have, Should Have, Could Have, or Won't Have. Must-Have count must not exceed 5. Total effort for Must+Should must fit within the target timebox.</statement>
        <rationale>Without a hard cap on Must-Haves, scope creep makes MVPs into 6-month projects. The cap forces real trade-off decisions rather than deferring them to "later".</rationale>
      </rule>

      <list>
        <item>Must Have (60% of scope): non-negotiable; product fails to deliver core value without these.</item>
        <item>Should Have (20% of scope): important but has workarounds; include if time allows.</item>
        <item>Could Have (15% of scope): nice-to-have; cut first under time pressure.</item>
        <item>Won't Have: explicitly excluded from this version; documented to prevent scope creep.</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="kill-signal-requirement">
      <p>Every MVP scope document must include a kill signal: the specific evidence that would prove the hypothesis wrong and stop the project. Example: "If fewer than 10% of users complete the core flow within 2 weeks, shut down."</p>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Every MVP scope document must include a kill signal: the specific evidence that would prove the hypothesis wrong and stop the project. Example: "If fewer than 10% of users complete the core flow within 2 weeks, shut down."</statement>
        <rationale>Without a kill signal, an MVP becomes an unfalsifiable experiment. Teams will ship regardless of what they learn, because there is no pre-agreed failure criterion to act on.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="six-step-scoping-process">
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Write the problem statement using this template: "For [target user] who [has this problem], our MVP will prove that [hypothesis] by delivering [core outcome] in [timeframe] with [constraints]."</statement>
        <rationale>The template forces explicit hypothesis statement before scoping begins. Scope without a hypothesis produces features without a learning goal.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Answer: "What is the ONE thing this product must do well?" Apply the value test: if you remove this feature, is the product useless? If yes, it is core value. If no, it is not.</statement>
        <rationale>Every scope decision derives from the core value. Features that do not support or enable the core value are candidates for Won't Have regardless of how good they are on their own.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Brain-dump all features first, then categorise each as Core (product doesn't work without it), Important (users would miss it), Nice-to-have (users can wait), or Out of scope.</statement>
        <rationale>Categorising before applying MoSCoW prevents anchoring on the first few ideas. The full dump also creates the Won't Have list, which is as important as the Must Have list.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Assign each feature a MoSCoW priority. Verify: Must-Haves do not exceed 5, total Must+Should effort fits the timebox. If either check fails, cut Must-Haves before extending the timeline.</statement>
        <rationale>Extending the timeline to accommodate scope is the default failure mode. The constraint forces real prioritisation instead of deferring trade-offs to engineering.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Run five checks before locking scope: solves core problem end-to-end, first user can complete core job without future features, value delivered is testable, buildable in target timeframe, has a testable hypothesis.</statement>
        <rationale>Scope that fails any check will fail in production. End-to-end validation is the most commonly skipped check — partial flows deliver no value even when they function correctly.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Write explicit completion criteria: feature list with acceptance criteria, definition of "good enough" quality, what to measure or learn, and the next decision after MVP results arrive (validate → build, invalidate → pivot).</statement>
        <rationale>MVP without a definition of done runs indefinitely. The next-decision field closes the loop: teams must decide in advance what they will do with the results.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="examples-and-antipatterns">
      <example type="good" title="Time Tracking App">
        <note>Problem: freelancers forget to track time and lose billable hours. Starting feature dump: 40+ features including mobile app, team features, integrations, advanced reports, budgets, etc.</note>
        <note>MVP scope (4 weeks): Must Have — start/stop timer (core functionality), project selection (assign time), basic report (see tracked time), simple invoice (get paid). Won't Have: mobile app (responsive web suffices), team features (solo focus), integrations (manual for now), advanced reports (spreadsheet export).</note>
        <note>Learning goal: will users actually track time daily? Kill signal: if fewer than 40% of registered users log time on 3+ days in the first 2 weeks, validate a different approach.</note>
      </example>

      <example type="good" title="Course Platform">
        <note>Problem: course creators struggle with tech setup. MVP scope (6 weeks): Must Have — upload video/text lessons (core content), paywall/payment (must monetize), student access control (protect content), basic progress tracking (show value).</note>
        <note>Won't Have: quizzes (manual feedback), certificates (v2), community features (use external Discord), mobile app (responsive web), advanced analytics (basic counts only).</note>
        <note>Learning goal: will creators pay $29/month for simplicity over full-featured competitors? Kill signal: if 0 of 20 early-access invitees pay after trial, pivot pricing or positioning.</note>
      </example>

      <antipattern>
        <description>More than 5 Must-Have features.</description>
        <reason>Every item added to Must-Have extends the timeline and narrows the learning. With 10 Must-Haves, the MVP is a 3-month project. Cap at 5 and demote the rest.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <antipattern>
        <description>No Won't-Have list.</description>
        <reason>Without explicit exclusions, scope creep enters through "just one more thing" requests. The Won't-Have list is a public commitment that prevents renegotiation of every cut feature.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <antipattern>
        <description>No learning goal or kill signal.</description>
        <reason>An MVP without a hypothesis is just a small product launch. Without a pre-agreed failure criterion, teams ship regardless of results and call it validated.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <antipattern>
        <description>MVP takes 6 months to build.</description>
        <reason>If it takes 6 months, it is not minimum. Revisit scope, cut Must-Haves further, or use micro-MVPs to validate assumptions before building.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Building MVP without weekly user feedback.</description>
        <reason>Assumptions invalidated at week 2 can redirect the remaining build. Waiting until launch to discover the hypothesis is wrong wastes all remaining build time.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>

    <templates>
      <template path="templates/mvp-scope-doc.md" purpose="Full MVP scope document: problem statement, feature scope by MoSCoW category, constraints, learning goals, definition of done."/>
      <template path="templates/mvp-quick-check.md" purpose="Five-question quick validator: solves one problem, delivers value today, minimum feature list, deferrals, timeline fit."/>
      <template path="templates/lint-scope.py" purpose="Python validator: checks must-have count, learning goal, kill signal, wont-have list, and effort vs budget."/>
    </templates>

